# OVG Platform Production Excellence Rules

## General Principles
- All code must be "production excellence" grade: no quick fixes or sloppy logic.
- Prefer modular, scalable components under 300 lines.
- Always use strict TypeScript types; avoid 'any' at all costs.

## State & React Hooks
- NEVER call setState synchronously within an effect body (prevents cascading renders).
- All functions passed to useEffect or as props MUST be wrapped in useCallback.
- Every useEffect and useCallback must have a complete dependency array.

## Performance & Next.js
- Use the Next.js <Image /> component instead of native <img> tags for optimization.
- Ensure all components are optimized for Core Web Vitals.

## Error Handling & Logging
- Prefix unused catch variables with an underscore (e.g., `_err`).
- Do not leave console.log statements in production code.

## Verification Workflow
- After every file modification, you MUST run `npm run lint` on the affected file.
- If linting fails, self-correct immediately before reporting completion.

## Hardware Lifecycle Management
When managing WebAudio or MediaStream objects, all hardware-accessing functions must be triggered only within an explicit user-gesture event (e.g., onClick). Avoid initializing AudioContext or MediaRecorder in useEffect or async callback chains to prevent browser autoplay blocking."

## Resource Cleanup Integrity
"When writing cleanup functions for hooks, verify the distinction between 'Hardware Cleanup' (closing mics/streams) and 'Lifecycle Cleanup' (closing audio contexts). Never call .close() or .pause() on shared persistent resources (like a global AudioContext) within a per-pipeline cleanup function."

## State-Machine Synchronization
"Avoid 'loading' or 'busy' states that rely on implicit completion. Always pair async requests with a corresponding try...finally block that ensures state flags (like isProcessing or isSpeaking) are reset to idle, regardless of whether the request succeeded or failed."